  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The address, Thou, O king, is here an absolute clause, and is not resumed till ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". By this address all that follows regarding Nebuchadnezzar is placed in definite relation to Belshazzar. The brilliant description of Nebuchadnezzar's power in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " has undeniably the object of impressing it on the mind of Belshazzar that he did not equal his father in power and majesty. Regarding וגו עממיּא, see under ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and with regard to the Kethiv זאעין, with the Keri יעין, see under ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". מחא is not from מחא, to strike (Theodot., Vulg.), but the Aphel of חיא (to live), the particip. of which is מחי in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", contracted from מחיא, here the part. מחא, in which the Jod is compensated by the lengthening of the vowel a4. Accordingly, there is no ground for giving the preference, with Buxt., Ges., Hitz., and others, to the variant מחא, which accommodates itself to the usual Targum. form. The last clause in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " reminds us of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 2:6-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Daniel brings to the remembrance of Belshazzar the divine judgment that fell upon Nebuchadnezzar (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). רם is not the passive part., but the perf. act. with an intransitive signification; cf. Winer, 22, 4. תּקף, strong, to be and to become firm, here, as the Hebr. חזק, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 7:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of obduracy. העדּיו, 3rd pers. plur. imper., instead of the passive: they took away, for it was taken away, he lost it; see under ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Winer, 49, 3. שׁוּי is also to be thus interpreted, since in its impersonal use the singular is equivalent to the plur.; cf. Winer. There is no reason for changing (with v. Leng. and Hitz.) the form into shewiy, part. Piel. The change of construction depends on the rhetorical form of the address, which explains also the naming of the ערדין, wild asses, as untractable beasts, instead of בּרא חיות (beasts of the field), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 4:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (23). Regarding the Kethiv עליה, see under ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 4:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and for the subject, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 4:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (25), 29 (32).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]